<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="85" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="85">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="85">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Macrocheilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Macrocheilus vitalisi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitalisi">Macrocheilus vitalisi</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Macrocheilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Macrocheilus binotatus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="binotatus">Macrocheilus binotatus</taxonomicName>
from Sumatra, but as stated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Andrewes, HE" journalOrPublisher="Zoologische Medemeelingen uitgegeven door s'Rijks Museum van Natuurlijke Historie te Leiden," pageId="14" pageNumber="91" pagination="54 - 78" title="Some keys to Sumatran Carabidae, together with descriptions of further new species." volume="14" year="1931">Andrewes (1931)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Macrocheilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Macrocheilus binotatus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="binotatus">Macrocheilus binotatus</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Macrocheilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Macrocheilus vitalisi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitalisi">Macrocheilus vitalisi</taxonomicName>
by &quot;the dark colour, the elytral spot oblong and red; the upper surface generally is more coarsely and less densely punctuate, the genae are contracted more sharply to the neck, the sides of the prothorax are less sinuate behind, the elytral intervals more convex, with punctuation along the side more widely spaced and coarser&quot;. In addition, according to our examination, the anterior seta of the labrum is closer to the apical margin in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Macrocheilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Macrocheilus vitalisi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitalisi">Macrocheilus vitalisi</taxonomicName>
than in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Macrocheilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Macrocheilus binotatus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="binotatus">Macrocheilus binotatus</taxonomicName>
and the 4th maxillary palpomere is cylindrically dilated in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Macrocheilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Macrocheilus vitalisi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitalisi">Macrocheilus vitalisi</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
